so-ansi-language: EN-US;\">·<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">        </span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">Low volatility, low carbon monoxide emissions (ecological compatibility)</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 504px;\"><img src=\"images/banners/1_small.jpg\" alt=\"\" />                           </td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table style=\"width: 1199px; height: 5px;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 1189px;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 12pt 0cm 3pt; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; border: none; padding: 0cm;\"> <span style=\"color: black; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 10.5pt;\">Some motor oils shall to meet special, additional requirements. Thus, multiple-viscosity oils supplied with macro-polymers, are required to have anti-wear thermal-mechanical stability. Marine diesel engine oils</span><span style=\"color: black; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 10.5pt;\">  </span><span style=\"color: black; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 10.5pt;\">are required to be water-resistant and low emulsifiability with water, power-saving engine oils</span><span style=\"color: black; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 10.5pt;\">  </span><span style=\"color: black; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 10.5pt;\">-are required to have anti-frictional, rheological</span><span style=\"color: black; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 10.5pt;\">  </span><span style=\"color: black; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 10.5pt;\">properties. Two struck petroleum engines run special specification oils. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 6pt 0cm; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"> </p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 6pt 0cm; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"> <span style=\"color: black; font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 18pt;\">SAE motor oil viscosity grades</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 6pt 0cm; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">Viscosity and  dependence on given  temperature (ranging from ambient temperature after cold start in winter time  to maximum operating  temperature in summer time )   is one of  the  main properties of motor oil.  Full description of  compatibility  of  temperature-viscosity properties   with  requirements of  different  engines, i.e. viscosity grades  is provided  in SAE J300 grading system (classification).  Motor oils  are classified to 17 grades – from 0W to 60  - based on their viscosity characteristics. 8 winter grades  (0W, 2,5W, 5W, 7,5W, 10W, 15W, 20W, 25W) and  9 summer grades  (2, 5, 7,5, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60).  Letter W designates Winter grade, thus cold temperature performance.   Other than minimum viscosity characteristics at temperature of 100C, these grades have threshold for pumping  at cold temperatures on the. Minimum pumpability temperature is the coldest temperature the oil passes and lubricates.  Its reffered to as minimum viscosity temperature required for safe start of engine.  Multi-grade oil viscosity grade consists of set of numbers, first denotes highest value of dynamic viscosity at low temperatures (frost) and   second defines  kinematic viscosity range of summer grade oil  at a temperature of 100 °C and dynamic viscosity at temperature of  150 °C. Methods used for measurement according to SAE J300, provides comprehensive information on maximum and minimum operational temperatures allowing the start of engine. In the process of cold start,   oil pump sends  the oil under pressure, preventing dry friction of   sliding units of engine.  HTHS  stands for High Temperature High Shear Rate.  This testing method allows the measurement of stability of oil  viscosity characteristics under severe operational conditions and at higher temperatures. Great majority of modern motor oils in markets are multi-grade, thus meet the minimum/ maximum viscosity requirements  at low and high temperatures.   Multigrade oils  are designated with set of numbers. First  - viscosity rate at  negative temperatures, second – viscosity rate at  high temperature (above 0) </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 6pt 0cm; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 6pt 0cm; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: init