AE 10W</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">SAE 20W-50</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">Oil shall preserve its qualities (properties) at changing temperatures. Designated with one (single-grade) or two numbers (multi-grade). The W denotes a \"winter grade\" from the days when oils were only monograde oils. The smaller is the number, the better it is to use in cold winter time. 0 is the minimum grade.  Number   without   “W” denotes summer  oil and indicates the preservation of body of oil at high operational loads. The bigger the number, the better it is to use in hot summer time. 60 is the top grade.</span> <span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">Presence of letter W – denotes winter grade, while absence denotes summer grade. </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"mso-yfti-irow: 2; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: center; line-height: normal;\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">API</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">API SJ/CF</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">API SF/CC</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">API CD/SG</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">API CE</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">API CE/CF-4</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">API SJ/CF-4, EC I</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">Defines operational qualities of the oil. Designation of letter (S) Service – denotes oils for gasoline (petrol) engines while (C) commercial – denotes oils for diesel engines. It is followed by letters which quality level for appropriate engines; thus  for petrol engines  it ranges from A to J, and for diesel engines from A to F (G).   Quality increases in linear order according to alphabet.   Number 2 or 4, followed by aformentioned letters, designate two-stroke and four-stroke engines, respectively.   Universal oils can be applied for either.   They are designated with SG/CD or CD/SG. Former specification, denote preference for gasoline, when latter preference for diesel engine.  EC letter combination defines oil’s  Energy Conserving characteristic. Roman figure I speaks to fuel-efficiency (saving petrol or diesel) over 1.5%, II – 2.5 % and III  - over 3%</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"mso-yfti-irow: 3; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: center; line-height: normal;\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">ACEA</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">ACEA A3-96,</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">B3-96</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">ACEA A2, B2</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">Defines quality characteristics of oil. There are 3 grades. A- for petrol engines, B – for (auto) diesel engines  E for truck diesel engine.  It is followed by numbers defining the quality of given oil. The bigger the number, the better is the quality, capable to operate under severe conditions of load and speed. For instance, A3-96,   means that oil meets A3 specification of ACEA  introduced in 1996</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"mso-yfti-irow: 4; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: center; line-height: normal;\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">CCMC</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">CCMC G4, D1</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">CCMC G2</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">Is obsolete European classification of oil quality. Oils are classified according to 3 grades: (G)  gasoUne – for petrol engines, (D) for truck diesel engines, (PD) for automobile petrol engines. Number standing after  grade designation, denote the quality level. The bigger the number, the higher is the quality.   </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"mso-yfti-irow: 5; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: center; line-height: normal;\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">MIL-L</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">MIL-L-2104A</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">MIL-L-46152D</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\"> </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">NATO-CODE</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\"> </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black; mso-themecolor: text1; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">US Military specification for oils. Similar to API grading system. Appraises the quality level of oil.  MIL-L-2104 for diesel engines and MIL-L-46152 for petrol engines.  Letters followed by numerical designation, denote quality level; for petrol engines  ranging from A to D, while for diesel engines from A to E. Quality increases in linear (alphabetic) order. NATO CODE –is considered the best grade for    petrol and diesel engines  </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"mso-yfti-irow: 6; mso-yfti-lastrow: yes; height: 7.3pt;\">\r\n<td style=\"padding: .75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt; height: 7.3pt;\">